{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:33:50.978854+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 3b0f2572474ab4ac8636eb4d2b4974a3159686d8)", "id": "lc_10ad0e9c-70f3-47a7-b2b4-483c10bbc720"}, {"type": "text", "text": "\"\"\"Token-bucket rate limiter backed by a Redis Lua script.\"\"\"\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom importlib import resources\nfrom typing import Tuple\n\nimport redis\n\n\n_SCRIPT = resources.files(\"ratelimit_redis\").joinpath(\"bucket.lua\").read_text()\n\n\nclass Limiter:\n    def __init__(self, redis_url: str, capacity: int, refill_per_sec: float) -> None:\n        self._r = redis.Redis.from_url(redis_url, decode_responses=False)\n        self._capacity = capacity\n        self._refill = refill_per_sec\n        self._sha = self._r.script_load(_SCRIPT)\n\n    def check(self, key: str, cost: int = 1) -> Tuple[bool, int]:\n        bucket_key = f\"rl:{{{key}}}\"  # hash-tag for cluster compatibility\n        result = self._r.evalsha(\n            self._sha,\n            1,\n            bucket_key,\n            str(self._capacity),\n            str(self._refill),\n            str(cost),\n        )\n        allowed = bool(result[0])\n        remaining = int(result[1])\n        return allowed, remaining\n", "id": "lc_4883ccac-4430-45b8-9cb1-b5c7aff84208"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "636cd2dd-fd4f-4e52-98d5-c6d967966bcd", "tool_call_id": "call_09bb68f0f8ad44a9869df8dc", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:33:50.979395+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 6f7e05edddbece2620a49be972026f6da3d7c8c0)", "id": "lc_529c9f95-655f-4d16-8e89-6aed7dcb93b4"}, {"type": "text", "text": "from .limiter import Limiter\n__all__ = [\"Limiter\"]\n__version__ = \"0.1.0\"\n", "id": "lc_e5c76908-0288-48d5-9822-efff4aba30b9"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "ebf9eb77-113f-43b7-b59a-ffc8546b70dd", "tool_call_id": "call_8eec7515826748bd9192de42", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:33:50.988173+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 39f9dd70b04b84aafe72caf640fd6a1ccdfee39f)", "id": "lc_042a7d5d-a553-417f-ba03-9f0bfc8ef01d"}, {"type": "text", "text": "-- bucket.lua: atomic token-bucket consume.\n-- KEYS[1]   = bucket key\n-- ARGV[1]   = capacity\n-- ARGV[2]   = refill per second\n-- ARGV[3]   = cost\n--\n-- The function returns {allowed (0/1), remaining tokens (int)}.\n--\n-- Stored state at KEYS[1] is a hash with fields:\n--   tokens : last observed bucket level (float, stored as string)\n--   ts     : Redis-server wall clock at last update (ms, integer)\n--\n-- Atomicity: this script runs as a single Redis command (EVALSHA), so\n-- the refill + consume sequence is not interleaved with any other\n-- client's evalsha against the same key. Reproducing the same logic\n-- as a sequence of GET + SET commands from the Python client would\n-- not be safe, even though Redis itself is single-threaded; the\n-- network round trips between separate commands open a race window.\n\nlocal key      = KEYS[1]\nlocal capacity = tonumber(ARGV[1])\nlocal refill   = tonumber(ARGV[2])\nlocal cost     = tonumber(ARGV[3])\n\nlocal now_ms = redis.call(\"TIME\")\nnow_ms = now_ms[1] * 1000 + math.floor(now_ms[2] / 1000)\n\nlocal state = redis.call(\"HMGET\", key, \"tokens\", \"ts\")\nlocal tokens = tonumber(state[1])\nlocal last_ts = tonumber(state[2])\n\nif tokens == nil or last_ts == nil then\n    tokens = capacity\n    last_ts = now_ms\nend\n\nlocal elapsed_sec = math.max(0, (now_ms - last_ts) / 1000.0)\ntokens = math.min(capacity, tokens + elapsed_sec * refill)\n\nlocal allowed = 0\nif tokens >= cost then\n    tokens = tokens - cost\n    allowed = 1\nend\n\nredis.call(\"HMSET\", key, \"tokens\", tostring(tokens), \"ts\", tostring(now_ms))\n-- Set TTL so unused buckets expire (10x time to fully refill, plus a floor)\nlocal ttl = math.max(60, math.ceil(capacity / refill * 10))\nredis.call(\"EXPIRE\", key, ttl)\n\nreturn {allowed, math.floor(tokens)}\n", "id": "lc_4cbb3366-c027-4e03-bcdf-31a44d829698"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "bc87d851-231d-45e4-ae7c-20c4a595d8cb", "tool_call_id": "call_8568b5226a724e3ab7044db0", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:34:10.417509+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Great, I now have the complete picture. Here's the detailed explanation:\n\n---\n\n## `Limiter.check()` — Full Walkthrough\n\n### Python Side (`limiter.py`)\n\n**Inputs:**\n\n| Parameter | Type | Default | Description |\n|-----------|------|---------|-------------|\n| `key` | `str` | *(required)* | A logical rate-limit key (e.g. a user ID, IP address, API endpoint name). |\n| `cost` | `int` | `1` | How many tokens this request costs (weight). |\n\n**Returns:** `Tuple[bool, int]`\n- `allowed` (`bool`) — `True` if the request is permitted, `False` if it was rejected.\n- `remaining` (`int`) — Integer number of tokens left in the bucket after this check.\n\n**What the Python code does step by step:**\n\n1. **Builds the Redis key** — It wraps the caller-supplied `key` with the pattern `rl:{<key>}`. The curly braces `{…}` are Redis Cluster hash tags that ensure all keys for the same logical key land on the same shard.\n\n2. **Calls `EVALSHA`** — It invokes the pre-loaded Lua script (identified by `self._sha`) on Redis with:\n   - **1 key**: `rl:{<key>}`\n   - **3 arguments** (all stringified): the bucket's `capacity`, the `refill_per_sec` rate, and the request `cost`.\n\n3. **Interprets the result** — The Lua script returns a two-element array `[allowed, remaining]`. The Python code casts `result[0]` to `bool` and `result[1]` to `int`, then returns them.\n\n---\n\n### Redis/Lua Side (`bucket.lua`) — The Token-Bucket Algorithm\n\nThe script runs **atomically** inside Redis (single EVALSHA command, no interleaving with other clients). Here's every step:\n\n1. **Read the current wall-clock time** — Calls `redis.call(\"TIME\")` and converts it to milliseconds (`now_ms`). This is the Redis server's clock, not the client's.\n\n2. **Load stored state** — Does an `HMGET` on the key to read two hash fields:\n   - `tokens` — the last known bucket level (float, stored as string).\n   - `ts` — the timestamp (ms) of the last update.\n\n3. **Initialize on first use** — If either field is `nil` (key doesn't exist yet), the bucket is initialized to **full capacity** and the timestamp is set to `now_ms`.\n\n4. **Refill** — Calculates how many seconds have elapsed since the last update (`elapsed_sec`), then adds `elapsed_sec * refill` tokens. The result is clamped to `capacity` (tokens never exceed the max).\n\n5. **Consume** — Checks if `tokens >= cost`:\n   - **Yes →** subtracts `cost` from `tokens`, sets `allowed = 1`.\n   - **No →** tokens are left unchanged (no deduction), `allowed = 0`.\n\n6. **Persist state** — Writes the updated `tokens` and `now_ms` back to the hash via `HMSET`.\n\n7. **Set TTL** — Calls `EXPIRE` on the key with `max(60, ⌈capacity / refill * 10⌉)` seconds. This auto-cleans idle buckets.\n\n8. **Return** — Returns `{allowed, floor(tokens)}` back to the Python caller.\n\n---\n\n### Side Effects on Redis\n\n| Effect | Key pattern | Type | Detail |\n|--------|-------------|------|--------|\n| **Hash created/updated** | `rl:{<key>}` | `HASH` with fields `tokens` and `ts` | Written every time `check()` is called (even on rejection). |\n| **TTL refreshed** | `rl:{<key>}` | `EXPIRE` | Reset on every call. Idle keys auto-expire after `max(60, 10 × capacity/refill)` seconds. |\n| **Script loaded once** | *(script cache)* | `SCRIPT LOAD` | Done in `__init__`, not per-call. |\n\nThere are **no other side effects** — no pub/sub, no lists, no sorted sets. The entire limiter state for every key lives in a single Redis hash per logical key.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 958, "prompt_tokens": 7037, "total_tokens": 7995, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 24, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 5952, "cache_write